3.5 Diabetic encephalopathy
Clinical studies have substantiated the therapeutic effects of GLP-1 RAs in humans. For instance, the use of Exendin-4 resulted in significant cognitive improvement in elderly patients with diabetes, independent of glycemic control [
16
]. In this study of 138 elderly diabetic patients, treating diabetes with Exendin-4 substantially improved their mini-mental status exam scores (MMSE) without correlating with Hemoglobin A1c (HgbA1c) levels. This finding supports a direct neuroprotective effect rather than simply improving glucose metabolism [
16
]. In addition, Liraglutide may enhance cognitive function in patients with T2DM in the context of mood disorders [
80
]. After a 4-week treatment with Liraglutide, there was a significant improvement in the Trail Making Test-B and composite Z-scores of several neuropsychiatric scales in patients with depression and bipolar disorders [
82
]. While further research is needed with more extensive and diverse populations, these findings suggest the potential clinical use of GLP-1 RAs in addressing cognitive decline associated with diabetic encephalopathy.
